<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-710-867  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 710 867.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Dec 17 1990 n300 p34(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IS budgets: cutting costs, but not corners; next year's increasein the IS budget will be the smallest ever for many firms.andO;(information systems) (Cover Story)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Leibs, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Information systems (IS) budgets for 1991 will barely keep pacewith inflation, the smallest increase in history for manycompanies, despite mounting pressure for MIS executives to use newtechnologies and quantify the return on their investments.andP;  Thetrend is exacerbated by the economic downturn in the economy.andO;Corporate IS budgets will not be cutting back on networktechnology or microcomputers.andP;  The outlook is bleaker for midrangecomputers, with less than 50 percent of InformationWeek readerssurveyed planning to purchase in this area during the next threeyears.andP;  The demand for mainframes will increase, motivated byexpansion in multimedia applications, communications and otherresource-intensive technologies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TrendsReader SurveyEquipment AcquisitionMicrocomputersPreview of Coming YearMainframe ComputersMISBudgeting.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   DP budget growth. (graph)Technology acquisition. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>